check_na <- function(x){
  x %>%
    select(everything()) %>%
    summarise_all(funs(sum(is.na(.))))
}

Exploratory Data Analysis

product_category <- inner_join(product, category, by = "sub_category")
order_product_category <- inner_join(order_product, product_category, by = "product_id")

order_product_category %>% 
  group_by(sub_category) %>% 
  summarise(total_products =  sum(quantity)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(sub_category, total_products), y = total_products)) +
  geom_col(fill="darkorchid") +
  geom_text(aes(label = total_products), vjust = 1.6, color = "white", size = 3.5) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Product Performance by Sub Category",
       x = "Sub Category",
       y = "Total Products Sold")

Findings for Management (1)

The most ordered product subcategory is binders, at 5,968, while the least ordered product subcategory is copiers, at 334. Notable underperforming products are copiers, machines, supplies, bookcases, envelopes, and fasteners. Some of these items are expensive one-time purchases, like copiers and machines, so it makes sense for there to be fewer orders of these items. However, items like envelopes and fasteners are items that are typically purchased in large quantities, so it is surprising that these items are underperforming. Perhaps we should look into this further.

# Profit Calculation
profit <- order_product_category %>%
  group_by(product_id) %>%
  summarise(product_profit = sum(unit_price * quantity * (1 - discount))) %>%
  ungroup()

ord_prod_profit <- inner_join(order_product_category, profit, by = "product_id")
ord_prod_profit2 <- inner_join(ord_prod_profit, orders, by = "order_id")
profit_loc <- inner_join(ord_prod_profit2, location, by = "postal_code")


profit_loc %>% 
  group_by(state, category) %>%
  summarise(state_profit =  sum(product_profit)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(state, state_profit), y =  state_profit, color = category)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Profit by Category and State",
       x = "State",
       y = "Total Profit",
       color = "Category")

Findings for Management (2)

California and New York are the states that bring in the highest amount of profit. Furniture is by far the most profitable category in California, and it is not the most profitable category in most other states. Perhaps we should start better marketing furniture to other states.

profit_loc %>% 
  group_by(discount, category) %>%
  summarise(disc_profit =  sum(product_profit)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = discount, y =  disc_profit, color = category)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Profit by Discount and Category",
       x = "Discount",
       y = "Total Profit",
       color = "Category")

Findings for Management (3)

There does not appear to be a correlation between discounted items and higher profits. In fact, the company gets more profit from items that are not discounted. Perhaps we should consider restructuring our discount offerings.

 profit_loc %>% 
  group_by(sub_category) %>%
  summarise(sub_cat_profit =  sum(product_profit)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(sub_category, sub_cat_profit), y =  sub_cat_profit)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkorchid") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Profit by Sub Category",
       x = "Sub Category",
       y = "Total Profit")

Findings for Management (4)

Fasteners, envelopes, and labels bring in the least amount of profit. Fasteners and envelopes are also in the list of underperforming products based on quanitity of orders. Perhaps we should consider halting our production of fasteners and envelopes and put more of our focus on furniture, which brings in more profit.

Findings for Management (5)

Binders are the best performing in terms of order quantity, but are fourth in terms of profit. Perhaps we should consider raising the price of binders slightly to increase profit for this item.

ord_prod_season <- inner_join(order_product_category, orders, by = "order_id")
ord_prod_season <- ord_prod_season %>%
  mutate(qtr = paste("Q", quarter(order_date)))

ord_prod_season %>% 
  group_by(sub_category, qtr) %>% 
  summarise(total_products =  sum(quantity)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(sub_category, total_products), y = total_products, color = qtr)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Product Performance by Sub Category",
       x = "Sub Category",
       y = "Total Products Sold",
       color = "Quarter")

Findings for Management (6)

Q1 is the worst performing quarter for all subcategories. Perhaps we should up our marketing efforts during this time of year.

profit_season <- inner_join(profit, ord_prod_season, by = "product_id")

profit_season %>% 
  group_by(sub_category, qtr) %>% 
  summarise(total_profit =  sum(product_profit)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = sub_category, y = total_profit, color = qtr)) +
  geom_point() +

  labs(title = "Seasonal Profit by Sub Category",
       x = "Sub Category",
       y = "Total Profit",
       color = "Quarter")

Findings for Management (7)

Chairs are extremely seasonal in terms of profits. Seasonal chair profits range from (250,000 in Q1 to 640,000 in Q4). We should further investigate what causes so many people to buy chairs in Q4.

profit_season %>% 
  group_by(qtr) %>% 
  summarise(total_profit =  sum(product_profit)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = qtr, y = total_profit)) +
  geom_col(fill = "darkorchid") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(title = "Quarterly Profit",
       x = "Sub Category",
       y = "Total Profit")

Findings for Management (8)

Q4 is the most profitable quarter, almost double Q1’s profits. We should focus more of our marketing efforts on Q1 to make our profit a bit more steady throughout the year.

We could focus furniture and office supplies sales in this region, since there are obviously fewer corporate offices that need high tech tools in this region.

Findings for Management (10)

In general, I am surprised not to see more blue dots (technology) on the map. We seem to sell a lot of office supplies throughout the country, but I expected to see technology to be more prominent in the big cities.

Before I created these graphs, I created a variable “day_yr” that stores the average daily riders per week day, for both 2011 and 2012. On the graphs this is demonstrated by one point representing the 2011 average for that week day, and to its right, a point representing the same week day average in 2012.

Based on these graphs, it is obvious that the total number of riders per day is determined mostly by the registered users, not the casual users. The peaks and slopes of the “total users” graph is quite similar in shape to the “registered users” graph. Additionally, it is clear that 2012 was a much more successful year across the board, which is why I separated each week day into 2011 and 2012 values to graph separately. Management should take note of this fact and separate 2011 and 2012 data for future calculations.

for (i in seq(3, 19, 2)) {
  
  # Make a knn spec
  knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(neighbor = i) %>% 
    set_engine("kknn") %>% 
    set_mode("classification")
  
  # Use the knn spec to fit the prepared training data
  knn_fit <- knn_spec %>% 
    fit(time_of_day ~., data = bikes_juiced)
  
  # Evaluate the model with the training data
  train_knn_fit <-  knn_fit %>% 
      predict(bikes_juiced) %>% 
      bind_cols(bikes_juiced) %>% 
      metrics(truth = time_of_day, estimate = .pred_class) %>% 
      mutate(k = i)
  
  # Evaluate the model with the testing data
  test_knn_fit <- knn_fit %>% 
      predict(bikes_test_baked) %>% 
      bind_cols(bikes_test_baked) %>% 
      metrics(truth = time_of_day, estimate = .pred_class) %>% 
      mutate(k = i)
  
  # Create summary performance evaluation dataframes
  if (i == 3) {
  summary_train_knn_fit <- train_knn_fit
  summary_test_knn_fit <-  test_knn_fit
  } else {
  summary_train_knn_fit <- bind_rows(summary_train_knn_fit, train_knn_fit)
  summary_test_knn_fit <- bind_rows(summary_test_knn_fit, test_knn_fit)
  }

}

If my model had worked properly and the accuracy estimates were different numbers for each k value I tested, I would choose the lowest k value with the highest accuracy (but not equal to 1, as that suggests overfitting).

       y = "Predicted Median Riders", 
       x = "Actual Median Riders") +
  coord_obs_pred()

Since my model gave me problems with the accuracy estimates for the k values, I tested, I was unsure of the best k value to use for my model so I tested a few values as I created this regression. I ultimately chose to use a k value 3, since the points seemed to be better fitted to the line than with a k value of 5, which is the default k value. The regression here is linear. We can approximate what the output from the model should be by looking at the points nearest to the predictor line.

Prep Data

segments_recipe <- recipe(segmentation ~ ., data = segments_train) %>%
  step_downsample(segmentation) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_medianimpute(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_dummy(segmentation, preserve = TRUE, one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  prep()

Juice and Bake

segments_juiced <- juice(segments_recipe)

segments_test_baked <- bake(segments_recipe, new_data = segments_test)

segments_train_baked <- bake(segments_recipe, new_data = segments_train)

Test k Values

for (i in seq(3, 19, 2)) {
  
  # Make a knn spec
  segments_knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(neighbor = i) %>% 
    set_engine("kknn") %>% 
    set_mode("classification")
  
  # Use the knn spec to fit the prepared training data
  segments_knn_fit <- segments_knn_spec %>% 
    fit(segmentation ~., data = segments_juiced)
  
  # Evaluate the model with the training data
  segments_train_knn_fit <-  segments_knn_fit %>% 
      predict(segments_juiced) %>% 
      bind_cols(segments_juiced) %>% 
      metrics(truth = segmentation, estimate = .pred_class) %>% 
      mutate(k = i)
  
  # Evaluate the model with the testing data
  segments_test_knn_fit <- segments_knn_fit %>% 
      predict(segments_test_baked) %>% 
      bind_cols(segments_test_baked) %>% 
      metrics(truth = segmentation, estimate = .pred_class) %>% 
      mutate(k = i)
  
  # Create summary performance evaluation dataframes
  if (i == 3) {
  segments_summary_train_knn_fit <- segments_train_knn_fit
  segments_summary_test_knn_fit <-  segments_test_knn_fit
  } else {
  segments_summary_train_knn_fit <- bind_rows(segments_summary_train_knn_fit, segments_train_knn_fit)
  segments_summary_test_knn_fit <- bind_rows(segments_summary_test_knn_fit, segments_test_knn_fit)
  }

}
